<subSubSection id="7BB36558FF941D5C7B3FFD82FD650D20" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" type="description">
<paragraph id="331636D3FF941D5C7B3FFD82FDD80A15" blockId="3.[270,653,523,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">
3. 
<taxonomicName id="F4A94D50FF941D5C7B14FD82FD2C0A75" authority="(Carpenter, 1888)" baseAuthorityName="Carpenter" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[293,653,523,548]" class="Crinoidea" family="Comasteridae" genus="Comaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Comatulida" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="nobilis">
<emphasis id="01DDEAC1FF941D5C7B14FD82FE740A72" bold="true" box="[293,469,523,548]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">Comaster nobilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="57384B22FF941D5C7BD0FD82FD270A75" author="Carpenter, P. H." box="[481,646,524,548]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" pagination="1 - 402" refId="ref17451" refString="Carpenter, P. H. 1888. Report upon the Crinoidea collected during the voyage of H. M. S. Challenger, during the years 1873 - 76. Part II. The Comatulae. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger, Zoology 26: i - x, 1 - 402, pls 1 - 70." type="journal article" year="1888">Carpenter, 1888</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
[Japanese name: Hana-umishida]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="331636D3FF941D5C7A84FDE3FF510CFF" blockId="3.[156,768,621,1686]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="01DDEAC1FF941D5C7A84FDE3FE9F0AD4" bold="true" box="[181,318,621,645]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">Morphology.</emphasis>
Centrodorsal thin, slightly raised from level of radials, 
<quantity id="F4519B36FF941D5C7B20FD00FE270AF4" box="[273,390,654,678]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" metricValueMax="5.2" metricValueMin="4.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" unit="mm" value="4.8" valueMax="5.2" valueMin="4.4">4.4–5.2 mm</quantity>
across. No functional cirri, except few rudimentary ones and scars. Radials exposed, length 0.3 times of centrodorsal diameter. IBr series composed of 2 ossicles, IIBr of 4(3+4), IIIBr of 2 on outer and of 4(3+4) on inner side of rays, and IV–VIBr of 4(3+4); proximal rays fused by additional interradial plates present, making calyx aborally solid. Arms up to 
<quantity id="F4519B36FF941D5C7BC1FCDFFDD20B39" box="[496,627,849,873]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04135" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" unit="mm" value="104135.0">104, 135 mm</quantity>
long; brachials shorter than broad, with distal ends everted; first arm syzygy at br 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7B26FC13FE900BFA" attach="left" box="[279,305,925,939]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">3+4</subScript>
; distal intersyzygial intervals 4. Comparative pinnule length PD&gt;&gt;P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7BBDFC30FE350B9D" attach="left" box="[396,404,958,972]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">1</subScript>
&gt;P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7B86FC30FE1E0B9D" attach="left" box="[439,447,958,972]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">2</subScript>
=P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7BD2FC30FE4A0B9D" attach="right" box="[483,491,958,972]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">3</subScript>
=P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C783FFC30FDB70B9D" attach="left" box="[526,534,958,972]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">4</subScript>
=P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7808FC30FDE00B9D" attach="left" box="[569,577,958,972]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">5</subScript>
; PD enlarged. Terminal combs present as far as P 
<subScript id="AF2D3496FF941D5C7BD8FC50FDA30BBD" attach="left" box="[489,514,990,1004]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">3–5</subScript>
, consisting of 7–17 segments; combs of PD with single, knob-like small teeth; ones of following pinnules with teeth paired, both straight, confluent with lateral margins of pinnule segments; paired teeth on proximal few segments fused into transverse bar. Disk remarkably large, five to eight times as wide as centrodorsal, smooth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="331636D3FF941D5C7A84FB39FEC40CA1" blockId="3.[156,768,621,1686]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="01DDEAC1FF941D5C7A84FB39FEAD0C9E" bold="true" box="[181,268,1207,1231]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">Posture.</emphasis>
Fully exposed on rocky pinnacles, with arms in multilayered arrays.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="331636D3FF941D5C7A84FB76FD650D20" blockId="3.[156,768,621,1686]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">
<emphasis id="01DDEAC1FF941D5C7A84FB76FED90D41" bold="true" box="[181,376,1272,1296]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">Coloration in life.</emphasis>
Various with the most common pattern being arms of yellow to orange and pinnules blotched with white, black, yellow and orange. Some animals almost entirely white with some pinnules blotched with black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7BB36558FF941D5C7A84FAF4FF7D0DA5" pageId="3" pageNumber="312" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="331636D3FF941D5C7A84FAF4FF7D0DA5" blockId="3.[156,768,621,1686]" pageId="3" pageNumber="312">
